<br>
Of myself, you ask?  But what is there to tell?  A thousand tales, of joy and saddness, terror and triumph, meetings and partings.... <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  her brow wrinkles slightly</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->... births and deaths.<br>
<br>
Shall I tell the tale of the day I met the rogue who stole my heart and soul, and gave me at once more joy and sorrow than any gentle being should be expected to endure?<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> A shadow passes across her face, and her arms wrap themselves around her as she shudders just a little.</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> Or perhaps you should like to hear the tale of the marriage that almost wasnt, and the wicked gnomes that nearly destroyed it.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  Liani falls silent for a moment, letting her eyes close as she composes herself.  As the moments pass, her face smoothes, and brightens once more... and at last she reopens her eyes and Keats can see within them the reborn spark of her customary mirth. </i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
Or perhaps it is meerly the tale of how this place came to be that you wish?<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  Letting her arms fall to her sides, Liani purses her lips and issues a sharp and patterned whistle, which brings a pixie trickster to flutter at her side.  Liani leans close to the tiny creature and murmers something in it's ear then smiles as the pixie nods her head and flutters off at high speed. </i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
Tell me, good Sir, what story you would hear, and I shall do my best to enlighten you.  The tale of my sister, who let her shame consume her and rob her of all joy, until she met Tunare at last and begged to stay by her side forever?<br>
<br>
Or perhaps the story of my niece, who... if the Queen be kind... shall never know the painful secret of her heritage and the family that would destroy her if it could?<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  The pixie returns, accompanied by many others.  Between them, they bear a lute case that seems to be made of some uniquely tanned and stained leather.  They deposit it, gently, upon Liani's lap before moving off to hover in an expectant group near the wall.  Liani raises hands that tremble just a touch, running them gently over the leather case.  Her practiced fingers find the all but hidden clasps and open them, pushing back the lid to reveal an ancient and intricately carved lute laying in a bed of forest green velvet.  <br>
<br>
A sigh escapes her as she at last clasps her hands around it and lifts it free, allowing the pixies to once more drift forward and remove the case.  As she settles the lute upon her lap, she once more lifts her eyes to meet Keats'. </i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
What shall it be then, my fine friend?  Joy, or sorrow?  Pain, or soothing?  Fear, or frolick?  Or, perhaps... something else entirely?<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  And with that, she grins, and her fingers strum the strings of the lute cradled in her lap just once... sending the sparkle of magic winging through the air around them both. </i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> <p><img src="http://mywebpages.comcast.net/ebisha/liani2.jpg
