<br>
The elder twin was quiet and serious, her spirit called to the service of the forest and dedicated to the goddess Tunare.  Fiercely loyal, she excelled at the skills taught her by the ranger's guild she was sworn to, and would give the very shirt off her back or even her life if need be, to save one whom she called friend.<br>
<br>
The younger twin was bouisterous and outgoing, full of fun and laughter and love.  As with her sister, it was obvious early in her life that this childs spirit was chosen by Erollisi and her path lay with those who dedicated thier lives to the magic of music.<br>
<br>
When the sisters were still very young and mainly untested... no more than 6 or 7 seasons... they often joined thier fellow young defenders in keeping the orc menace at bay.  There came a day... perhaps chosen by the gods, as such things often are... when the sisters set out to fight the orc menace and ultimately found themselves deep within the fortress of crushbone.  <br>
<br>
All was well... for a time. The sisters fought hard and long and with much success... until they found themselves upon the hill where the orcs trained thier own young fighters.  Though the twins fought bravely, they soon found themselves overmatched and knew that they would be meeting thier respective gods this day.  But as the young bard tried desperately to drag the wicked crushbone trainer's attention from her sister long enough for the young ranger to heal herself to some degree and perhaps prolong thier battle that much more, suddenly the tide of battle turned.  <br>
<br>
The vicious trainer shrieked in agony and spun around to face a new opponent who, with stunning accuracy, had buried a dagger deep into his back.  At almost the same moment, a deep voice intoned &quot;By Tunare, be healed!&quot; and the young ranger's wounds began to close and her ebbing strength return.  Before long, the sisters stood triumphant over the fallen body of the orc trainer and thier eyes took in the sight of thier saviours.  <br>
<br>
The ranger's eyes were drawn to the handsome and stoic face of the High Elven paladin whose prayer had saved her life and whose sword had joined her own in taking his life.<br>
<br>
The bard's eyes, however, could not be dragged from the face of the dark eyed rogue whose well placed dagger had turned the tide of battle, allowing victory to come from certain defeat.  There was a smile upon his lips and a glint of mischief in his eyes... and yet, behind that, she could sense something far deeper.<br>
<br>
From that moment on, the four were all but inseperable.  They spent every possible waking moment together, fighting side by side... defending each other as good and true friends do.  As time passed, the fought further afield... traveling together as much as thier respective guild duties allowed them to do.  Before long it was more than obvious that the Queen of Love had worked her special magic that day... for though the four were all fast friends, it was more than apparent that the two pairs... ranger and paladin.... bard and rogue... were tied with bindings of the heart and soul.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Liani blinks once, across eyes that still shine though no longer with tears, and a soft smile spreads itself across her lips as she returns her sight to the here and now and meets the expectant gaze of her fellow bard. </i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
But THAT... is another story.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  And, with a mischivious wink, she scoops up her long forgotten cup and takes a deep drink of now tepid coffee.</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> <p><img src="http://mywebpages.comcast.net/ebisha/liani2.jpg
